What Is a Chatbot?


a chatbot is a software system designed to engage in conversational exchange through text or voice, functioning as an interface between computational models and natural language input. its defining characteristic is not simply automation, but the ability to interpret prompts and generate responses in a manner that resembles dialogue. historically, chatbots were conceived as narrow interaction tools intended to answer questions, guide users through workflow, or simulate basic conversation within tightly constrained domains.

early chatbots operated almost entirely on predefined rules and decision trees. their behavior was deterministic, meaning each input corresponded to a fixed output or a small set of scripted responses. while effective for customer service menus or form-based interactions, these systems lacked adaptability and failed quickly when language deviated from expected patterns. intelligence, in this stage, was largely an illusion created by careful scripting rather than learned behavior.


