Machine Learning Vs. Deep Learning


the distinction between machine learning and deep learning is best understood not as a rivalry between techniques, but as a difference in how representation and learning are organized. machine learning, in its classical form, relies on explicitly defined features derived from domain knowledge. the model's task is to learn relationships between these features and an outcome, making performance highly dependent on how well the problem has been framed in advance. in this sense, machine learning embeds much of the intelligence upstream, in the design of the data and the assumptions encoded into the model.






















